segments.text: Maxine was kind of, Maxine Davenport, Emanuel's then wife, was kind of den mother to the philosophy department.
And we all had parties.
Every weekend we had parties.
And they were lovely long parties where there was a lot of drinking going on.
And people brought their kids and they set them out in play pens under the trees.
And around six o'clock somebody would go out for fried chicken.
And sometimes a party would last from noon until two in the morning.
And we would talk about philosophical issues and literary issues as well as local things.
In fact, more than local things.
And so it was really a good time.
There were always, it was not just the ten of us, because each of these people had an attachment.
It was other people who were interested in philosophy.
I would say there would be about sixteen at each of these things.
And this went on for quite a while.
And many of them were interested in philosophy.
And Emanuel Davenport was very enthusiastic about kind of philosophy for ordinary people.
That was his shtick.
And so we would get in really good discussions in which everyone took part.
As opposed to now you get to a philosophy group and it's always very specialized, the discussion.
So people cannot participate unless they are, unless they know the language, walk the walk, talk the talk, and so forth.
It wasn't that way then.
It was open discussion.
Anybody who had an interest could easily get into the discussion.
Emanuel did interesting things.
For instance, he joined Mensa.
And then he suggested to Hugh that Hugh would be an appropriate member for Mensa, too.
And so I got irritated and I said, well, what about me?
I'm going to join this group, too.
So we went down to Austin to take the intelligence test, which was really goofy.
And we joined Mensa.
And then Emanuel had Mensa parties.
And these were really fun.
There would be a couple of Aggies, sometimes in uniform.
There would be some brilliant person who never had a chance to get out of a restrictive life.
There would be a handful of people from the university.
And these people would go over to his house and he'd provide refreshments and we'd talk about stuff.
So this was kind of when the philosophy department got a little bit tired of one another.
And this was a way of refreshing it.
But one thing I noticed is that he always had these chess sets and so forth set out so that anybody who wanted to can indulge in this kind of thing.
But nobody ever touched any of this stuff.
There were puzzles, chess sets.
People just talked.
And there was gossip, too, at these things.
I didn't think they were that much different from the regular philosophy parties.
But there was less alcohol because there were students.
I think we had beer.
And that was it.
But Emanuel always had some problems.
He always had some project.
He did a lot of work for the BCLU.
He was active in the Unitarian Church.
He was a wonderful auctioneer.
They were always auctioning stuff off for benefits.
And Emanuel was just great at that.
And so I remember those first few years actually in a kind of beery haze but very pleasant with Emanuel at the helm of the philosophy department.
And I remember that.
I think he was in the department head.
And I remember he was, officially, he was the department head.
Did he operate as a department head or department chair?
He operated as a department chair.
He did everything democratically.
And I believe that was an all Anglo-Mal department?
Yes, it was.
It was indeed.
Okay.
All right.

hard to say because they didn't have, they didn't party.

had a reputation, so they figured that I'd be up for, game for their parties too.

to get together on Friday afternoons at a restaurant.

the man.

That's right.

man should be in that post.

There was
a lot of junk going on then.

actually fights having to do with walking on the grass.
And then, there was a lot of
bass.

I participated in the moratorium, but I didn't really connect
this anti-military feeling about the war to Rutter, because of course that wasn't his
war.
So I would say I did not really have much of an impression of him.
Did you notice early on Aggie traditions?
Oh, yes.
First of all, there was a business about the lawn.
Then there was Bonfire.
I
attended Bonfire at that time.
When we passed on heads to David Stewart, David Stewart had
the, for some reason, the urge to kind of force traditions on everybody.
He made people
go to Yale practice, for instance.
I thought Yale practice was a totally disgusting tradition.
It's kind of funny that I should have participated in so many parties and not like Yale practice,
but Yale practice seemed to me just out of control.
There was an article in the Texas
Observer about the Corps some years ago, and I remember reading that.
This was very anti-Corps,
really, but it had all the pictures of all the traditions, and I remember thinking, gee,
this is really a crazy place to be.
But I was never either strongly for, or I was not an anti-tradition person.
On the other
hand, there are quite a few traditions that I didn't really buy into.
All right.

Alright, this is a note to the typist.
This will go in as an editorial
note.
I was dean of faculties at this
time and this is the last commencement that I attended before going
in the summer of 1980 to become the new
president of the University of Texas at El Paso.
This is the last
commencement in May of 1980.
We then had commencements
on Friday afternoon, Friday night, and Saturday morning.
This is the Saturday morning commencement.
NM students then and
now graduate in alphabetical order by college,
by major, and by last name.
Melanie
Zentgraf's undergraduate major was biomedical science,
which is the only undergraduate major
in the College of Veterinary Medicine.
So she was
the last student, because of her last name,
beginning with the letter Z, from the last college
and that was the third commencement.
Her family, I learned later,
had thought that we had deliberately rigged it so that she would be
the last of the last of the last.
That part is not true.
Our commencement speaker at that event was
William P. Hobby, Jr., the lieutenant governor, Bill Hobby
from Houston.
And while the diplomas were being passed out, Lieutenant Governor
Hobby motioned to me to come up from my seat on about three rows behind him
and sit next to him.
And he told me that when I got out to UTEP
to stay in contact, I should stay in contact with him, that he would
try to help me since we'd known each other for about 20 years.
And he
said such marvelous things as maybe I can help UTEP with a special
item or something or other.
As I began to note that we were about
to finish the commencement, I was starting to get up from my seat and go back
to the back row when I heard some hissing.
I turned to him and said, oh my goodness.
He said, what is it?
I said, I don't know, but
there are some people out there hissing, which means they're mad about something,
particularly the corps members.
And I turned to my right and I saw
that Melanie Zentgraf was about to come up on the stage.
And I said,
oh my goodness, here comes Melanie Zentgraf.
He said, gee, Monique, she's
really pestered me.
She's been a pain.
She's come over.
She's
written letters.
Melanie's problem was
that she had wanted to be on the fish drill team, in the A&M band,
in the Ross Volunteers.
And for all three of those
hopes, she had gotten lame excuses and
had been not allowed to compete for one of those positions.
The point of this editorial note
is that within two or three feet of where I was
seated, she came up to receive her diploma.
President Jarvis Miller handed it to her.
She took it in her right hand,
shifted it to her left hand, then extended her right
hand to him.
And he very quietly said,
no way, I'm going to shake your hand.
The Lieutenant Governor and I and many, many people in the audience kind of
held our breath and gasped a bit.
She then turned to Bob Lacy,
the Registrar who was handing the diplomas
to President Miller, being sure that he handed the right
diploma to him at the right time.
She extended her hand to Mr. Lacy
and Mr. Lacy said, ma'am, I'm not involved in this argument.
She then turned to Don Carter, who was the
then on the staff of the Registrar, and he said, ma'am,
let's keep the line moving.
So she went off stage
and being the last degree recipient, everyone noticed it.
Paragraph.

when Dr. Miller was summoned over to a
special meeting of the Board of Regents, he walked in
and they announced to him that he had been terminated
effective that day at 5 o'clock,
that he had been terminated as President.
They read him a statement
and the first thing I understand that they said to him
on an ad lib basis was, you refuse to shake hands
with an Aggie graduate.
Melanie
is a person whose role at A&M
is symbolically very
important because she did not receive
fair treatment, particularly on that day,
and the person making this statement learned that you
shake hands with every student and give every student at least the credit
that they deserve.
